      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute brisk walk or very easy jog to wake up the legs. Focus on relaxed breathing and upright posture.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, conversational pace — you should be able to speak full sentences without gasping. This is your aerobic base-building effort. If you need walk breaks, take them freely.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a walk for the final 5 minutes. Take a few deep breaths and do light leg swings or calf stretches.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute easy walk before you start your run. This primes your cardiovascular system and gets your muscles moving before asking more of them.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3–5 minutes after finishing. Gentle quad, hamstring, and calf stretches held for 20–30 seconds each work well here.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Monday run is your weekly aerobic foundation session. At your current fitness level, easy running builds the capillary density and mitochondrial efficiency that everything else rests on. The pace range of 7:00–8:00 per km is intentionally gentle — faster does not mean better here. If it feels almost too easy, that's a sign you're nailing it.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Steady Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5 minutes of easy walking or a very gentle jog. Let your body gradually shift gears.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":22,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into your easy conversational pace. Focus on consistency — same effort throughout rather than starting fast and fading. Walk breaks are completely fine whenever needed.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradual walk to finish. Notice how your body feels compared to Monday — some fatigue is normal, but you should still feel in control.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Take 5 minutes to walk before you begin running. Midweek runs can feel stiffer than Monday, so a slightly longer walk warm-up is absolutely fine.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes and stretch gently. Pay particular attention to your calves and hip flexors, which tend to tighten with new running routines.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday gives you a second aerobic stimulus mid-week while keeping volume manageable. At 3 days per week, each run carries real value — this session reinforces the adaptations you started on Monday. The goal is the same: easy, controlled, conversational effort. You're accumulating time on feet, and that consistency is what drives long-term improvement.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Weekend Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":465,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":465,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute walk. The long run should never feel rushed from the first step — give yourself permission to ease in slowly.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":465,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at your easiest, most comfortable pace. This is slightly slower than your weekday easy runs — that's intentional. Walk breaks of 1–2 minutes are encouraged any time you feel your breathing get labored. Aim to finish feeling like you could have gone a little further.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 5 minutes. Take this time to scan your body — notice any areas of tightness or discomfort and make a mental note for your next run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute walk, possibly longer if it's cold or you feel stiff. The long run is about duration and aerobic development, not speed, so there is no rush to start running.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes and spend 10 minutes on full-body stretching — quads, hamstrings, calves, hip flexors, and glutes. Hydrate well after finishing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run — the cornerstone of 5K preparation and endurance development. Even for a 5K goal, building your long run progressively teaches your body to sustain effort, improves fat utilization, and builds the mental confidence that comes from time on your feet. At 6 km this week, you're already extending beyond your current 5 km long run, which is a meaningful step. The slightly slower pace here is physiologically important — it keeps you in a fat-burning aerobic zone and ensures you can recover well for Monday.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
